title: RV Park Worries Lead Residents Who Remember 1994 Landslide
text:
RV Park Worries Lead Residents Who Remember 1994 Landslide October 26, 2015, 9:50 AM LEAD, SD - 
Some residents of Lead say a planned recreational vehicle park is in an area of unstable ground, and they worry it could have catastrophic effects. The planned park is adjacent to an area that was the site of a slow landslide in 1994 that threatened 30 homes and closed a mall. It cost about $5 million to stop, including $4 million in federal grant money. Resident Rene Larson says she and others worry that dirt work for the RV park could "trigger a horror to again visit our neighborhood." Mayor Jerry Apa says the RV park could boost the local economy. He says he's also aware of the concerns and expects robust discussion at a Tuesday meeting of the city's Planning and Zoning Board. Â© 2015 Associated Press. All rights reserved.
